text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Expansion: It can appear in both matching and contrasting polarity tag questions, eh?%0a:Author: Simon_Y%0a:Original: [[Articles.CanadianEh|CanadianEh]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.nithyas|nithyas]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 18.04.2021 - 14:45%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-175503-45460#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 10:55-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-175503-45460#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI thought there is an insteresting grammatical property of the "eh".%0a%0aIn standard English, a tagged question can only exist in certain polarity patterns. [Postitive(P), Negative(N)]%0a%0aa. Oh, you're still here, are you?    (P-P)%0a%0ab. That should be okay, shouldn't it? (P-N)%0a%0ac. He didn't do it, did he?           (N-P)%0a%0ad. *He didn’t do it, didn’t he?      *(N-N)%0a%0aAs you can see, a tag question cannot match the polarity of a negative sentence. However, the "eh" can appear in all of the combinations of polarity.%0a%0aa. Oh, you’re still here, eh?%0a%0ab. That should be okay, eh?%0a%0ac. He didn't do it, eh?%0a%0aAbove examples are all valid.%0a%0aThought this would make an interesting sidenote to the article.%0a%0aRef: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
