diff:1618782344:1618782344:=1,62d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Expansion: It can appear in both matching and contrasting polarity tag questions, eh?%0a%3c :Author: Simon_Y%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.CanadianEh|CanadianEh]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.nithyas|nithyas]]%0a%3c :Section: A%0a%3c :Completed: 18.04.2021 - 14:45%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I thought there is an insteresting grammatical property of the "eh".%0a%3c %0a%3c In standard English, a tagged question can only exist in certain polarity patterns. [Postitive(P), Negative(N)]%0a%3c %0a%3c a. Oh, you're still here, are you?    (P-P)%0a%3c %0a%3c b. That should be okay, shouldn't it? (P-N)%0a%3c %0a%3c c. He didn't do it, did he?           (N-P)%0a%3c %0a%3c d. *He didn’t do it, didn’t he?      *(N-N)%0a%3c %0a%3c As you can see, a tag question cannot match the polarity of a negative sentence. However, the "eh" can appear in all of the combinations of polarity.%0a%3c %0a%3c a. Oh, you’re still here, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c b. That should be okay, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c c. He didn't do it, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c Above examples are all valid.%0a%3c %0a%3c Thought this would make an interesting sidenote to the article.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ref: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
